---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import DocsSidebar from "../../components/DocsSidebar.astro";
---
<Layout
	title="Self-host · flipagent docs"
	description="Run the flipagent API yourself. Docker image, Postgres setup, environment variables, and deploy templates for Azure Container Apps."
>
	<div class="cmw cmw-bordered">
		<div class="docs-shell">
			<DocsSidebar />
			<article class="docs-content">
				<h1>Self-host</h1>
				<p class="lead">Run <code>@flipagent/api</code> on your own infrastructure. The whole API server is OSS. Only the proxy URL and your eBay developer keyset are env-shaped secrets.</p>

				<h2>Why self-host</h2>
				<ul>
					<li><strong>Your eBay app, your tokens.</strong> The hosted service uses <em>flipagent's</em> eBay app. Self-hosting means your users grant OAuth to <em>your</em> app, which is useful for white-labeling or for keeping eBay API quota under your own developer account.</li>
					<li><strong>Compliance / data residency.</strong> Cache rows + usage logs stay in your Postgres.</li>
					<li><strong>No metering.</strong> The hosted tier counter is enforced per API key; self-hosting drops the limit (your eBay quota becomes the real ceiling).</li>
				</ul>

				<h2>Minimum viable config</h2>
				<p>One env var gets you running:</p>
				<div class="code">
					<div class="code-head"><div class="dot-row"><span></span><span></span><span></span></div><span>.env</span></div>
<pre><code>{`DATABASE_URL=postgres://user:pass@host:5432/flipagent`}</code></pre>
				</div>
				<p>That's enough for the scrape-only path: <code>/v1/items/search</code>, <code>/v1/items/:id</code>, <code>/v1/categories</code>, <code>/v1/marketplaces/ebay/catalog</code>, <code>/v1/evaluate</code>, <code>/v1/ship/*</code>, <code>/v1/health</code>. Keys are issued by a CLI script. No GitHub OAuth, no Stripe, no eBay developer account needed.</p>

				<div class="code">
					<div class="code-head"><div class="dot-row"><span></span><span></span><span></span></div><span>shell</span></div>
<pre><code>{`docker compose up -d postgres
cp packages/api/.env.example packages/api/.env  # set DATABASE_URL
npm install
npm run --workspace @flipagent/api db:migrate
npm run --workspace @flipagent/api dev
# in another terminal: issue your first key
npm run --workspace @flipagent/api issue-key -- you@example.com standard`}</code></pre>
				</div>
				<p>Without <code>SCRAPER_API_VENDOR</code> + credentials the api scrapes from your server's IP, which eBay will rate-limit fast. For anything real you want a managed Web Scraper vendor (today: Oxylabs).</p>

				<h2>What works at each config level</h2>
				<table class="api">
					<thead>
						<tr><th>Feature</th><th>Env required</th><th>Without it</th></tr>
					</thead>
					<tbody>
						<tr>
							<td>Browse + sold scraping</td>
							<td><code>DATABASE_URL</code></td>
							<td>—</td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<td>Managed Web Scraper vendor</td>
							<td><code>SCRAPER_API_VENDOR</code> (default <code>oxylabs</code>) + <code>SCRAPER_API_USERNAME</code> + <code>SCRAPER_API_PASSWORD</code></td>
							<td>Direct from your server IP. eBay blocks fast.</td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<td>eBay REST passthrough (Browse, Inventory, Fulfillment, Finance)</td>
							<td><code>EBAY_CLIENT_ID</code>, <code>EBAY_CLIENT_SECRET</code>, <code>EBAY_RU_NAME</code></td>
							<td><code>503 ebay_not_configured</code> on those routes; Browse falls back to scrape</td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<td>Order API <span style="opacity:0.6">(Limited Release)</span></td>
							<td><code>EBAY_ORDER_APPROVED=1</code> after eBay tenant approval</td>
							<td><code>501 not_implemented</code> until approved</td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<td>Marketplace Insights REST <span style="opacity:0.6">(sold history)</span></td>
							<td><code>EBAY_INSIGHTS_APPROVED=1</code> after eBay program approval</td>
							<td><code>/v1/items/search?status=sold</code> falls back to the scraper (still works, slower + lossier)</td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<td>Sign-in dashboard</td>
							<td><code>BETTER_AUTH_SECRET</code>, <code>GITHUB_CLIENT_ID</code>, <code>GITHUB_CLIENT_SECRET</code></td>
							<td>Use the <code>issue-key</code> script instead</td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<td>Continue with Google</td>
							<td><code>GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID</code>, <code>GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET</code></td>
							<td>Sign-in still works via GitHub or email/password</td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<td>Password reset / verify email</td>
							<td><code>RESEND_API_KEY</code></td>
							<td>"Forgot password?" surfaces a not-configured message</td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<td>Stripe billing</td>
							<td><code>STRIPE_SECRET_KEY</code>, <code>STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET</code>, <code>STRIPE_PRICE_HOBBY</code>, <code>STRIPE_PRICE_STANDARD</code>, <code>STRIPE_PRICE_GROWTH</code></td>
							<td>Self-hosting → no metering, billing isn't relevant</td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<td>LLM same-product matcher (used internally by <code>/v1/evaluate</code>)</td>
							<td>One of <code>ANTHROPIC_API_KEY</code> / <code>OPENAI_API_KEY</code> / <code>GOOGLE_API_KEY</code></td>
							<td>Composite endpoints fall back to the unfiltered (raw) sold + active pools. Margin math still runs but the pools are looser. Search, sold history, ship still work either way.</td>
						</tr>
					</tbody>
				</table>

				<h2>LLM provider (for the same-product matcher)</h2>
				<p>The same-product matcher (used internally by <code>/v1/evaluate</code>) is the only feature that calls an LLM. It's provider-agnostic — pick whichever cloud you already have a key for. <code>LLM_PROVIDER</code> picks explicitly; otherwise the first key set wins (anthropic → openai → google).</p>
				<div class="code">
					<div class="code-head"><div class="dot-row"><span></span><span></span><span></span></div><span>.env (pick one)</span></div>
<pre><code>{`# Anthropic Claude — https://console.anthropic.com/
ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-...
ANTHROPIC_MODEL=claude-haiku-4-5         # default

# OpenAI — https://platform.openai.com/api-keys
OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-...
OPENAI_MODEL=gpt-5.4-mini                # default

# Google Gemini — https://aistudio.google.com/apikey
GOOGLE_API_KEY=...
GOOGLE_MODEL=gemini-2.5-flash   # default

# Optional: explicit pick when more than one key is set
LLM_PROVIDER=anthropic`}</code></pre>
				</div>
				<p>Self-hosters who don't care about LLM matching can skip this entirely — every other route works without it. <code>/v1/evaluate</code> still computes the market summary + evaluation math from whatever sold + active pools the server returns; it's only worse if the pools are unfiltered.</p>

				<h2>Hit <code>/v1/health/features</code> to see what's wired</h2>
				<p>Public, unauth, no DB hit. Self-host status page in one call:</p>
				<div class="code">
					<div class="code-head"><div class="dot-row"><span></span><span></span><span></span></div><span>shell</span></div>
<pre><code>{`curl http://localhost:4000/v1/health/features`}</code></pre>
				</div>
				<div class="code">
					<div class="code-head"><div class="dot-row"><span></span><span></span><span></span></div><span>response</span></div>
<pre><code>{`{
  "ebayOAuth":   false,
  "orderApi":    false,
  "insightsApi": false,
  "biddingApi":  false,
  "scraperApi":  true,
  "betterAuth":  false,
  "googleOAuth": false,
  "email":       false,
  "stripe":      false,
  "llm":         false
}`}</code></pre>
				</div>

				<h2>eBay developer setup (when you go beyond scraping)</h2>
				<ol>
					<li>Create a free account at <a href="https://developer.ebay.com/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">developer.ebay.com</a>.</li>
					<li>Create a production keyset under <strong>Application Keys</strong>. Copy <code>App ID (Client ID)</code> → <code>EBAY_CLIENT_ID</code> and <code>Cert ID (Client Secret)</code> → <code>EBAY_CLIENT_SECRET</code>.</li>
					<li>Under <strong>User Tokens → Get a Token from eBay via Your Application</strong>, register a RuName (eBay's redirect URI alias). Set the <em>Auth Accepted URL</em> to <code>https://your-host/v1/connect/ebay/callback</code>. Copy the RuName → <code>EBAY_RU_NAME</code>.</li>
					<li>Restart the api. <code>GET /v1/connect/ebay</code> now redirects to eBay's consent page; users come back via the callback and their tokens land in <code>user_ebay_oauth</code>, scoped to the calling API key.</li>
					<li>For the sandbox, set <code>EBAY_BASE_URL=https://api.sandbox.ebay.com</code> and <code>EBAY_AUTH_URL=https://auth.sandbox.ebay.com</code>.</li>
				</ol>

				<h2>App token vs user token</h2>
				<p>eBay issues two kinds of access token, and flipagent picks the right one per route. The split decides whether a call needs an OAuth-connected seller or just your keyset.</p>
				<ul>
					<li><strong>App token</strong> (<code>client_credentials</code>): minted from <code>EBAY_CLIENT_ID</code> and <code>EBAY_CLIENT_SECRET</code>. Cached ~110 min, shared across every caller. For catalog reads that don't act on a specific account.</li>
					<li><strong>User token</strong> (<code>authorization_code</code> → <code>refresh_token</code>): minted only after a seller clicks Allow on <code>/v1/connect/ebay</code>. Stored per API key in <code>user_ebay_oauth</code>. Required for any route that reads or writes that seller's account. One keyset can hold tokens for unlimited sellers; sellers don't need their own developer account, just a regular eBay account.</li>
				</ul>
				<table class="api">
					<thead>
						<tr><th>Route</th><th>Token</th><th>Needs connected seller</th></tr>
					</thead>
					<tbody>
						<tr><td><code>/v1/items/*</code> (active read)</td><td>App</td><td>—</td></tr>
						<tr><td><code>/v1/items/search?status=sold</code> (when Insights approved)</td><td>App</td><td>—</td></tr>
						<tr><td><code>/v1/categories/*</code>, <code>/v1/marketplaces/ebay/catalog/*</code></td><td>App</td><td>—</td></tr>
						<tr><td><code>/v1/listings/*</code></td><td>User</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
						<tr><td><code>/v1/sales/*</code> (orders, shipments)</td><td>User</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
						<tr><td><code>/v1/payouts/*</code>, <code>/v1/transactions/*</code></td><td>User</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
						<tr><td><code>/v1/policies/*</code>, <code>/v1/me/seller/*</code></td><td>User</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
						<tr><td><code>/v1/purchases/*</code> (when REST transport approved)</td><td>User</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
					</tbody>
				</table>
				<p><code>EBAY_SCOPES</code> is the space-separated list flipagent asks each seller to consent to. The default covers every user-token route the API exposes:</p>
				<div class="code">
					<div class="code-head"><div class="dot-row"><span></span><span></span><span></span></div><span>EBAY_SCOPES default</span></div>
<pre><code>{`https://api.ebay.com/oauth/api_scope
https://api.ebay.com/oauth/api_scope/sell.inventory
https://api.ebay.com/oauth/api_scope/sell.fulfillment
https://api.ebay.com/oauth/api_scope/sell.finances
https://api.ebay.com/oauth/api_scope/sell.account
https://api.ebay.com/oauth/api_scope/commerce.identity.readonly
https://api.ebay.com/oauth/api_scope/commerce.message
https://api.ebay.com/oauth/api_scope/commerce.feedback
https://api.ebay.com/oauth/api_scope/sell.marketing
https://api.ebay.com/oauth/api_scope/sell.marketing.readonly
https://api.ebay.com/oauth/api_scope/sell.analytics.readonly
https://api.ebay.com/oauth/api_scope/sell.payment.dispute
https://api.ebay.com/oauth/api_scope/sell.reputation`}</code></pre>
				</div>
				<p>The <code>sell.*</code> scopes ship standard with any production keyset; no extra opt-in in the developer portal. Trim the list to narrow what sellers grant (e.g. drop <code>sell.finances</code> if you don't surface payouts); the matching <code>/v1/payouts</code> and <code>/v1/transactions</code> calls will then 401 from eBay until the seller reconnects with the wider scope.</p>

				<h2>Marketplace Insights + Order API (eBay program approval)</h2>
				<p>Two capabilities need additional eBay-side approval beyond the standard developer keyset:</p>
				<ul>
					<li><strong>Marketplace Insights</strong> (sold-listing history). Apply at developer.ebay.com → Marketplace Insights. Once granted, set <code>EBAY_INSIGHTS_APPROVED=1</code>: <code>/v1/items/search?status=sold</code> then hits the REST endpoint with the app token (faster, cleaner data, <code>source: "rest"</code>). Without approval flipagent serves the same endpoint via the scrape transport, and <code>/v1/me/permissions</code> reports <code>marketplaceInsights: "scrape"</code>.</li>
					<li><strong>Order API</strong> (Limited Release). Lets your authenticated buyer place purchases via REST — flipagent's server posts to eBay directly. Apply at developer.ebay.com → Order API; once granted, set <code>EBAY_ORDER_APPROVED=1</code>. Until then <code>/v1/purchases</code> auto-falls-back: bridge transport when the user pairs the Chrome extension (richer in-page UX), or url transport otherwise (response carries <code>nextAction.url</code> pointing at the ebay.com listing for the user to click Buy It Now manually). All three resolve to the same <code>Purchase</code> shape; pick approval up later without breaking integrations.</li>
				</ul>

				<h2>Inspect a user's eBay scope tier</h2>
				<p>Once you've got a key plus an eBay-connected user, hit <code>/v1/me/permissions</code> to see the per-scope status. Useful for surfacing "your eBay account doesn't have <em>sell.fulfillment</em>, reconnect to enable shipment tracking" in your own UI:</p>
				<div class="code">
					<div class="code-head"><div class="dot-row"><span></span><span></span><span></span></div><span>response</span></div>
<pre><code>{`{
  "ebayConnected": true,
  "ebayUserName": "your-ebay-handle",
  "ebayUserId":   "ebay:1234567890",
  "scopes": {
    "browse":              "ok",
    "marketplaceInsights": "scrape",
    "inventory":           "ok",
    "fulfillment":         "ok",
    "finance":             "ok",
    "orderApi":            "approval_pending"
  }
}`}</code></pre>
				</div>

				<h2>(Optional) Run the dashboard locally too</h2>
				<p>The Astro app under <code>apps/docs/</code> is the same dashboard you see at flipagent.dev. To point it at your local api instead of <code>api.flipagent.dev</code>, set <code>PUBLIC_API_BASE_URL</code> and run the dev server:</p>
				<div class="code">
					<div class="code-head"><div class="dot-row"><span></span><span></span><span></span></div><span>shell</span></div>
<pre><code>{`PUBLIC_API_BASE_URL=http://localhost:4000 \\
  npm run --workspace @flipagent/docs dev`}</code></pre>
				</div>
				<p>Astro starts on <code>localhost:4321</code>. The dashboard at <code>/dashboard/</code> needs a session, which means Better-Auth env (<code>BETTER_AUTH_SECRET</code>, <code>GITHUB_CLIENT_ID/SECRET</code>) must be set on the api side. Skipping that? Just hit the api directly with the key from <code>issue-key</code>. The dashboard is optional for self-host.</p>

				<p>For production deploy of the dashboard, build with the same env: <code>PUBLIC_API_BASE_URL=https://api.your-host npm run --workspace @flipagent/docs build</code> and serve <code>apps/docs/dist/</code> behind any static host (Cloudflare Pages, Netlify, S3+CloudFront, …). The api also needs <code>APP_URL=https://your-dashboard-host</code> so eBay OAuth callbacks + Stripe success URLs land in the right place.</p>

				<h2>Deploy</h2>
				<p>The repo ships a Terraform module for Azure Container Apps + Postgres Flexible Server (<code>infra/azure/</code>). Anything that runs Postgres plus a Node 20 container works: Fly, Render, Railway, Cloud Run, ECS. Set <code>MIGRATE_ON_BOOT=1</code> so drizzle migrations run before the api starts (idempotent; revisit if <code>min_replicas</code> exceeds 1).</p>

				<h2>License</h2>
				<p><code>@flipagent/api</code> is FSL-1.1-ALv2: source visible, free for any non-competing use, converts to Apache 2.0 two years after each release. The OSS scraper, types, MCP server, and SDK packages are MIT.</p>
			</article>
		</div>
	</div>
</Layout>
